    "bloodline": {
      "name": "Bani Gwo-Samdi",
      "description": "Tremere doctrine on the subject of Blood Sorcery focuses on the strength of the thaumaturge's will and their mastery over Blood. Yet the relatively young magicians of House High Saturday also sought power from forces stronger than themselves: the “Lwa”, as the various houngans of the House called them, said to be spiritual intermediaries to the divine. Before the collapse of the Pyramid, most Tremere viewed the warlocks of House High Saturday as weak for seeking power via submission to these Lwa, and even more decried them for their practice of discussing the secrets of Thaumaturgy with non-Tremere.\n\nTonight, however, House High Saturday's most vocal detractors are dead; their clan has lost its power to compel adherence to orthodoxy; and their open trading of knowledge has given them an understanding of something most Tremere have little comprehension of: Oblivion.\n\nYour bloodline descends from this 300-year-old tradition of Vodou willworkers, their secrets being your birthright and your undead flesh being another body in service to the great Lwa. Staying true to the naming convention that spans all the way back to the (supposed) days of House Tremere's origins as a gathering of mortal magicians, most houngans identify themselves with the honorific of “bani Gwo-samdi”, roughly meaning “of House High Saturday”.",
      "merits": [
        {
          "name": "Friends on the Other Side",
          "value": 1,
          "description": "House High Saturday members don't just rely on each other; they have the wisdom of the Lwa to seek out as well, although these spirits can be just as capricious and petty as they can be useful.",
          "rules": "Once per chapter, you can meditate on a solution to a problem, providing you have enough time and the materials for enticing the proper Lwa, allowing you to roll two dice in a Skill you don't possess or adding two automatic successes in an area you already have familiarity with.",
          "notes": "",
          "purchased": true
        },
        {
          "name": "Veves & Chants",
          "value": 2,
          "description": "You learn Oblivion at the in-clan rate and do not need to drink the Blood of another Kindred to learn it.",
          "rules": "When you select Oblivion Powers, you may only select powers that grant Ranks in the Spectral School of Oblivion. Upon learning your first dot of Oblivion, you also gain a one-dot Folkloric Bane or Block Flaw.",
          "notes": "",
          "purchased": true
        },
        {
          "name": "Crossroads Bargain",
          "value": 3,
          "description": "House High Saturday always had allies outside the Pyramid and at least one group of necromancy practitioners who didn't want to kill them: the Samedi of the Hecata.",
          "rules": "Gain four dots to allocate between Contacts and Mawla assigned to Hecata. Calling on these Backgrounds invokes a transactional relationship, where a favor will be asked in exchange for the Hecata's aid.",
          "notes": "",
          "purchased": true
        },
        {
          "name": "Dernière Gorgée",
          "value": 4,
          "description": "When you take another Kindred's vitae, you steal a trace of their passage and leave a faint stain of your own in return. The House calls it the dernière gorgée: the \"final draught\" that lingers in the Blood like a bitter aftertaste, waiting for the moment the cup shatters.",
          "rules": "When another vampire dies, if you have tasted their vitae since your last feeding, you immediately become aware of their Final Death. Once per story, you may burn the last of their Blood from your system as they cross over by making a Rouse Check. If you do, the vampire returns as a wraith three hours after midnight, three nights after their death, at the location where they died.",
          "notes": "",
          "purchased": false
        },
        {
          "name": "Crise de Lwa",
          "value": 5,
          "description": "While their Hecata counterparts usually take a more iron-fisted approach to dealing with wraiths, High Saturday necromancers have cultivated a loyal retinue of ghosts at their side by giving them praise and offerings. The most precious offering being a Kindred's most valuable resource: their body. You have the curse and blessing of being a “cheval”, a necromancer uniquely susceptible to possession and said to be favored by the Lwa.",
          "rules": "- Upon purchasing this Merit, replace an Oblivion power of level two or greater with \"Unliving Anchor\". You do not need to satisfy the Amalgam prerequisite.\n- Instead of being only able to anchor one wraith to yourself, you can instead anchor a number of wraiths equal to your Oblivion dots.\n- You gain a +2 bonus when using Host Spirit targeting one of them.\n- Your entourage of spirits is passionate, but they are not mindless servants. Any failure on a Ceremony roll is treated as a Total Failure, resulting in one of your attendant spirits possessing you without your permission to pursue their own goals for the remainder of the scene.",
          "notes": [
            "Jean Ducheski-Francois I: Former first-mate and revenant of Caesar's from the late 1700s. The closest wraith to Caesar as both men have known each other for 3 centuries. Very level-headed and tactically minded but also becomes overly worried about his captain easily. Can take drastic measures in an attempt at protection.",
            "Rebecca Rossellini: A ghoul from the Giovanni gifted to Caesar that was killed in an internal spat during the early 1900s. Her mere presence makes the Hecata uncomfortable due to her hatred of her former family. Most intimidating wraith of the trio. Sees her relationship with Caesar as transactional and a path towards revenge.",
            "Ponticulus: A sorcerer turned wraith even older than Caesar that bonded with him from a fragment of Ceoris during the 2000s. Even in death he has a steady control over magic. He supports Caesar's rebuilding of High Saturday out of the desire to control what he sees as a potential figurehead of the Clan. Gets power-hungry on behalf of Caesar."
          ],
          "purchased": true
        }
      ]
    },
    "loresheet": {
      "name": "Revenant Family Ducheski",
      "description": "The Ducheski were once the Krevcheski, a family of scholars in Eastern Europe patronized by its nobles. The Tzimisce subjected them to years of experimentation, transforming the family into revenants, a hereditary line of ghouls born with a semblance of vampiric vitae in their veins but afflicted with a craving for the real thing. For a time, they served the clan faithfully, developing a knack for creating advanced clockwork devices for siege warfare and torture.\n\nWhen war broke out between the Tremere and the Tzimisce, the Krevcheski betrayed their masters, pledged fealty to the Tremere, and took their new name. They have served the clan in secret ever since, maintaining the Warlock's libraries, sanctums, and laboratories. The family is in decline; few are permitted to continue their line and even fewer are allowed to join the clan as Kindred. At least one member of this illustrious family is at your service.\n\nUnless stated otherwise, purchasing any level of this loresheet for the first time provides Retainer (•), representing the revenant. A Ducheski revenant is a ghoul built as a Weak Mortal that always has access to Auspex 1 and Blood Sorcery 1.",
      "merits": [
        {
          "name": "Nourishing Blood",
          "value": 1,
          "description": "While a revenant's vitae is nowhere near as potent as the Kindred, drinking it can be just as sustaining.",
          "rules": "When you feed from your Ducheski revenant, they are not subject to the Human slake penalty of your Blood Potency. Feeding from them never risks a Blood Bond. The revenant is still harmed by your feeding like a human would be.",
          "notes": "",
          "purchased": false
        },
        {
          "name": "Personal Library",
          "value": 2,
          "description": "The Ducheskis hold a wealth of knowledge within their dilapidated ancestral strongholds. Your revenant has added their personal library of ancient texts to yours, increasing your understanding of the world's mysteries.",
          "rules": "Choose two of these three Skills: Academics, Investigation, or Occult. Whenever you make a test with any Specialty in your chosen Skills, you receive one extra die, in addition to any applicable bonuses.",
          "notes": "",
          "purchased": false
        },
        {
          "name": "Research Team",
          "value": 3,
          "description": "You have a tight-knit family unit of three to five Ducheski revenants in your care.",
          "rules": "You receive Retainer (••) to represent them. Once per story, when you task your research team with studying a new Ritual, their dedication and teamwork allow you to learn the Ritual in half of the usual learning time.",
          "notes": "",
          "purchased": true
        },
        {
          "name": "Ritual Assistant",
          "value": 4,
          "description": "Your Ducheski revenant has a special aptitude for the story of Blood Sorcery, and can help enhance your magical techniques.",
          "rules": "When your revenant is present and helps you prepare a known Ritual, the Difficulty of the roll to activate it is reduced by 1. If more than one Ritual Assistant is present, the Ritual pool increases by one die for every two Ritual Assistants present after the first.",
          "notes": "",
          "purchased": false
        },
        {
          "name": "Ducheski Invention",
          "value": 5,
          "description": "You own a one-of-a-kind Ducheski creation.",
          "rules": "This could be one of their infamous clockwork devices, or even a modern technological marvel designed by a revenant in your service. Give the invention a name and function, and choose a Skill. Your Storyteller will name up to three components that make its function possible. The invention is a Specialty of that Skill that provides three extra dice when the invention is used in tasks involving that Skill. If it is damaged or destroyed, any Ducheski in your service knows how to fix it, if they have all the components available.",
          "notes": "",
          "purchased": false
        }
      ]
    },
    "timeline": [
      {
        "era": "Pre-Embrace",
        "startYear": 1699,
        "endYear": 1735,
        "affiliation": "nil",
        "details": "Born in the Asante Empire as the mixed race son of a soldier with no real knowledge of his mother, he is put into slavery at a young age when he is told his father has gone missing and has assumedly abandoned his duties.\n\nAt age 15 he is packed into a ship as he and thousands of others are purchased by Dutch landowners and taken to the colonies in the New World. He lives a torturous life underneath many changing masters, one of which happens to be the murderous privateer known as Edward \"Blackbeard\" Teach.\n\nAlmost the entirety of \"Black Caesar's\" mortal life was spent in slavery with half of it being as an indentured servant in the Asante Empire and the other half as a chattel slave in the Americas. He was sold from owner to owner until eventually he was set to be executed for an attempted escape which technically went as scheduled. However his death was staged as Jervais took the opportunity to recruit a nobody to serve as a loyal spy for him.",
        "locations": [
          "Asante Empire, Africa",
          "Colonies, the Americas",
          "Spanish Florida, Americas"
        ]
      },
      {
        "era": "A Time of Violence",
        "startYear": 1735,
        "endYear": 1804,
        "affiliation": "camarilla",
        "details": "For mortals, legends of the fearsome corsair \"Black Caesar\" begin to spread around both the Atlantic and the Pacific as he commits atrocities on behalf of his sire for House Goratrix which are reported as if they were acts of piracy.\n\n\"I don't care whose blood you'll have me shed. I felt nothing but fear when I was alive. Now I'll give the world a name and an image to fear in return.\"",
        "locations": [
          "Spanish Florida, Americas",
          "Vienna, Austria",
